2026-04-21 01:33:33 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Input Cable (+) 3', 'Control Output Cable (+) 3', 'Control Module 3 internal 12V path / switch contact'] hypothesis_explanation="Measurements show that +12 V from the PSU reaches Control Input Cable (+) 3, and that this conductor is continuous from the PSU up to its termination at Control Module 3. However, at the internal port of module 3 (port 'n', before the switch path), the conductor is floating/disconnected, and the outgoing +12 V conductor to module 4 is at 0 V even though its cable has nominal continuity.\n\nThis indicates that within Control Module 3 the 12 V path is open between the incoming +12 V terminal and the rest of the internal 12 V line / switch contact, or between the switch contact and the output terminal. Because the inspection panel cannot be opened, this appears as an internal wiring or switch failure that prevents +12 V from being passed downstream. This single open fault explains why modules 1–3 see proper 12 V/0 V, while all modules from 4 onward and the load measure 0 V on both conductors and why all downstream indicators and the lamp stay off. Replacing/repairing Module 3’s internal 12 V path (including its input and output + terminals and switch contact) is therefore the most likely fix."
